WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.000
My name is Joe Cheng. I am the CTO of Posit. Most days I co-lead the Shiny team with Winston Cheng.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:19.000
Shiny really started with a request from one of our users, one of our earliest users of RStudio IDE.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Professor Danny Kaplan asked us for an interactive way to present statistical and math concepts to students.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.000
And he knew R really well, so he wanted to do it with R.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:39.000
So it wasn't until probably a year after he had made this request that I stumbled onto a technology called Meteor

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:48.000
that was pushing this new, to me very alien, form of programming called reactive programming.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:54.000
And it took me a while to get my head around how it actually worked and a little digging through their source code.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:03.000
But finally, after I understood what they were doing, and some time had passed where I guess my brain had marinated it,

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:12.000
I woke up one morning and I just had this vision of HTML with no JavaScript in it,

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:18.000
just simple markup that had indicators of what elements were inputs and what elements were outputs.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:28.000
Combined that with reactive code written in R that would power that HTML interface

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:31.000
and tie it all together with a WebSocket connection.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:39.000
It really felt like this could be a way to build applications that were interactive enough to satisfy the needs of

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:44.000
not just Danny, but a lot of Dannys out there in the R world.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:52.000
And I think Shiny will always find its purest expression in R just because of how flexible the language is.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:02:00.000
But it's impossible to ignore how many people could benefit if we bring those same ideas to Python as well.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:10.000
The design of the language really prioritizes ease of understanding and ease of reading.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:21.000
Whereas I think in R we tend to favor concise expression of our ideas and maybe a certain elegance and symmetry.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:30.000
And in Python, readability, understandability, simplicity, those are valued more.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.000
So I think for some people, Python is just home.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.000
I mean, it's famously the second best language for anything.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:44.000
I think that's a label that Pythonistas probably wear with pride.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:55.000
And because Python is the second best language for anything, it means that if we want to reach more people with Shiny,

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:00.000
we can reach all those people for whom Python is useful. And that's a lot of people.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Thank you.

